How one agency turned existing leads into more revenue
 

 
                                                                                                                              
 

 

 

Hey Bob,

Ever feel stuck because every obvious growth move costs money you don’t have yet?

That’s where Jacob was.

Jacob runs a B2B marketing agency focused on SEO and content.

Demand wasn’t the issue.

Ideas weren’t the issue.

The problem was that every “just do more of X” suggestion required extra cash. More ads, more spend, more risk. And he didn’t have the revenue to comfortably reinvest at the top of the funnel.

Meanwhile, the leads he’d already paid for weren’t turning into momentum.

What he was really missing was a way to earn trust at scale — and do it in a way his prospects would actually see.

He’d try to explain his thinking on LinkedIn:
why most SaaS SEO strategies were outdated,
what was breaking because of generative AI,

and where teams were quietly losing traffic and revenue.

Sometimes those posts landed.

Most of the time, they didn’t reach the people he’d already talked to — even warm leads he was connected with.

Algorithms decided who saw what.

Jacob couldn’t rely on that to nurture his leads.

So he started a weekly newsletter.

Each issue did three things:
 

It agitated the problem.
He broke down real SEO shifts — generative search, declining click-throughs, content decay — and explained why they mattered to B2B teams.
 

It demonstrated expertise.
Not by pitching, but by showing how he thought through these problems, week after week, in plain language.
 

It kept him top of mind — predictably.
No algorithm. No hoping a post surfaced. He knew it landed in inboxes, with ~40% of people opening it consistently.
 
The result?

Prospects referenced the newsletter on calls.

Dormant leads replied months later to specific issues.

Deals that would’ve gone cold stayed warm — and eventually closed.

Existing clients expanded after seeing his thinking regularly.

Over a few months, that trust compounded into over $100K in new and expanded revenue.

The takeaway isn’t that newsletters are magic.

It’s that email is one of the few channels where you can reliably:
build trust,
surface problems prospects didn’t know they had,
and quietly position yourself as the obvious solution.

When people actually see your thinking every week, selling gets a lot easier.

Ready to finally drive more value from your list? 

